		By: Brian Habel		</title>
		<link>https://jamesclear.com/sleep-levers#comment-11636</link>

		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Brian Habel]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Sat, 27 Sep 2014 03:36:15 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://jamesclear-com.uar9g7bv-liquidwebsites.com/?p=6190#comment-11636</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[This is been one of my &#039;key pin&#039; habits that if I get right influences everything.  For the last 5 years I&#039;ve been waking with only 5 hours of sleep (I have to go the bathroom at that time incidentally) with inability to get back to sleep, about half the time.  I&#039;ve even changed my wind-down-program or show, to be in that morning time, when it has fluctuated to less than half the time being able to sleep, so as to minimize worrying-in-bed about it and other things.  It has been the hugest time waster in my life, this problem.  Things are in a decent range now, but I do fluctuate in getting to bed on time.  So, I&quot;ll start here; is the message, so as to not keep on having this inability to have structure based off this one problem.  So, once again, thank you for keeping at this game.  The best thing I&#039;ve come across to help me with this problem?  Dale Carnegie&#039;s book on mp3 onto my phone that he took 6 years to write called, &quot;How to Stop Worrying and Start Living&quot;.  The best pre-bed time body primer for getting to sleep almost every time:  http://marc.ucla.edu/mpeg/Body-Scan-for-Sleep.mp3  More subtle than you think, at least for me... try it!  The guy who shared it with me told me it has never failed him.  Pretty close to the mark if all the other stage is set.]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>This is been one of my &#8216;key pin&#8217; habits that if I get right influences everything.  For the last 5 years I&#8217;ve been waking with only 5 hours of sleep (I have to go the bathroom at that time incidentally) with inability to get back to sleep, about half the time.  I&#8217;ve even changed my wind-down-program or show, to be in that morning time, when it has fluctuated to less than half the time being able to sleep, so as to minimize worrying-in-bed about it and other things.  It has been the hugest time waster in my life, this problem.  Things are in a decent range now, but I do fluctuate in getting to bed on time.  So, I&#8221;ll start here; is the message, so as to not keep on having this inability to have structure based off this one problem.  So, once again, thank you for keeping at this game.  The best thing I&#8217;ve come across to help me with this problem?  Dale Carnegie&#8217;s book on mp3 onto my phone that he took 6 years to write called, &#8220;How to Stop Worrying and Start Living&#8221;.  The best pre-bed time body primer for getting to sleep almost every time:  <a href="http://marc.ucla.edu/mpeg/Body-Scan-for-Sleep.mp3" rel="nofollow ugc">http://marc.ucla.edu/mpeg/Body-Scan-for-Sleep.mp3</a>  More subtle than you think, at least for me&#8230; try it!  The guy who shared it with me told me it has never failed him.  Pretty close to the mark if all the other stage is set.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
		
