		<title>
		By: Inanna		</title>
		<link>https://jamesclear.com/sleep-levers#comment-11630</link>

		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Inanna]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Fri, 26 Sep 2014 14:26:54 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://jamesclear-com.uar9g7bv-liquidwebsites.com/?p=6190#comment-11630</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[I like this way of thinking about sleep. I think the same way, letting my body choose intensity and duration, while controlling wakeup time instead of bedtime.

Why? For me, getting out of bed when sleepy is a choice, while sleeping when I am not sleepy is impossible. 

If I get up at seven for three days, I start falling asleep around midnight and wake up rested. If I force myself to stay up late, or choose to sleep late for more than a day, I start feeling sleepy during the day.

After three days, or a week if I have really messed with my rhythm, my body readjusts and I feel awake. Most of the time it&#039;s really that simple.]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>I like this way of thinking about sleep. I think the same way, letting my body choose intensity and duration, while controlling wakeup time instead of bedtime.</p>
<p>Why? For me, getting out of bed when sleepy is a choice, while sleeping when I am not sleepy is impossible. </p>
<p>If I get up at seven for three days, I start falling asleep around midnight and wake up rested. If I force myself to stay up late, or choose to sleep late for more than a day, I start feeling sleepy during the day.</p>
<p>After three days, or a week if I have really messed with my rhythm, my body readjusts and I feel awake. Most of the time it&#8217;s really that simple.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
		
